===Verb===
{{en-verb}} {{tlb|en|American spelling}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give something color.
#: {{syn|en|dye|paint|stain|shade|tinge|tint}}
#: {{ux|en|We could '''color''' the walls red.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause (a pipe, especially a [[meerschaum]]) to take on a brown or black color, by smoking.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To apply colors to the areas within the boundaries of a line drawing using colored markers or crayons.
#: {{syn|en|color in}}
#: {{ux|en|My kindergartener loves to '''color'''.}}
# {{lb|en|of a person or their face}} To become red through increased blood flow.
#: {{syn|en|blush}}
#: {{ux|en|Her face '''colored''' as she realized her mistake.}}
# To affect without completely changing.
#: {{syn|en|affect|influence}}
#: {{ux|en|That interpretation certainly '''colors''' my perception of the book.}}
# {{senseid|en|portray as}} {{lb|en|informal}} To attribute a quality to; to portray (as).
#: {{syn|en|call}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Color''' me confused.}}
#: {{ux|en|They tried to '''colour''' the industrial unrest as a merely local matter.}}
# {{lb|en|mathematics|graph theory}} To [[assign]] colors to the [[vertex|vertices]] of a [[graph]] (''or'' the [[region]]s of a [[map]]) so that no two vertices connected by an [[edge]] (regions sharing a border) have the [[same]] color.
#: {{ux|en|Can this graph be 2-'''colored'''?}}
#: {{ux|en|You can '''color''' any map with four colors.}}
# {{senseid|en|change vowel}}{{lb|en|linguistics|usually of a {{glossary|phoneme}}}} To affect the quality of a [[speech]] [[sound#Noun|sound]], especially a [[vowel]].
#: {{ux|en|Many languages have a "neutral", roughly [[central]] vowel like {{IPAchar|/a/}} or {{IPAchar|/É™/}} which can be '''colored''' to a [[back]], [[rounded]] vowel like {{IPAchar|[o]}} by an adjacent [[labialized]] consonant, or to a [[front]], [[unrounded]] vowel like {{IPAchar|[e]}} by an adjacent [[palatalised|palatalized]] consonant.}}
#: {{ux|en|The [[Proto-Indo-European]] [[laryngeal]] ''*[[hâ‚‚]]'' often '''colors''' the neutral vowel ''*e'' with an ''[[a]]''-like quality, while ''*[[hâ‚ƒ]]'' results in a more ''[[o]]''-like quality; ''*[[hâ‚]]'' has no '''coloring''' effect.}}

